After discussion with  , I’ve decided to leave it out:

1. For ECDSA signing, both Ethers and Viem don’t expose a low-level API to allow direct signing of a specific `replaySafeHash`. EIP-712 signing must be done via `signTypedHash` for security reasons.

2. Coinbase owns the whole stack: frontend SDKs, wallet client. So they can do their replay safe ERC-1271 while showing the contents in the hash even tho its not nested EIP-712. 

Also, they are able to directly sign the `replaySafeHash` cuz they use WebAuthn instead of ECDSA.
If someone doesn’t use the whole Coinbase stack, then the hashes will still be opaque, and they can’t sign unless they use WebAuthn.
